7gv.title: The plan experiment
7gv.clickbait: Root page for describing the reason and the process for planning how to approach and navigate through AGI development.
7gv.text:
"The plan" is an experiment in collaborative discussion. The central topic is helping humans navigate development of AGI. Its development is a hard technical problem, and making sure that the way is developed is beneficial to all humans makes it even harder. In the mean time, there is a perceived aura of pressure. This pressure comes from multiple sources:

* Internal: this is a high stakes situation and people want to get it right.
* Newness: humans have never built an AGI before, so there are a lot of unknown unknowns.
* Us vs them perspective: people imagine that others are competing with them to get to AGI faster than they would. They imagine those people taking shortcuts in safety in order to speed up the timeline.
* Lack of clear communication: a lot of conversations about this happen in private.
* Lack of clear direction: there is no plan for people to follow or discuss.

This experiment exists to address all of these issues, by recognizing their manifestations in each individual. To fully address these issues, the plan has to be public.

## What's in the plan?

[National response framework](https://www.fema.gov/national-response-framework)%%note: The National Response Framework describes not only how the Federal government organizes itself to respond to natural disasters, terrorist attacks, and other catastrophic events but also the importance of the whole community in assisting with response efforts. The intended audience for this document is individuals, families, communities, the private and nonprofit sectors, faith-based organizations, and local, state, tribal, territorial, insular area, and Federal governments.%% provides a [detailed document](https://www.fema.gov/media-library-data/1466014682982-9bcf8245ba4c60c120aa915abe74e15d/National_Response_Framework3rd.pdf) describing how various organizations and federal governments can respond to an event of emergency. I imagine the final output of the plan to be something along these lines, although it'll be framed in a more proactive way.%%note: It's possible [NIMS](https://www.fema.gov/national-incident-management-system) is closer to what I'm looking for. It's "a systematic, proactive approach to guide departments and agencies at all levels of government, nongovernmental organizations, and the private sector to work together seamlessly and manage incidents involving all threats and hazardsregardless of cause, size, location, or complexityin order to reduce loss of life, property and harm to the environment."%%

Specifically, the plan will have these components:

* List of all the relevant organizations and people
* Various milestones for anticipating and measuring AGI progress
* Various suggested actions that should be taken once the milestones are reached
* Various events that might happen (e.g. a call to nationalize AGI development) and possible responses

## Execution

### Steps

1. Go through existing literature and extract the key portions. Use those to write the first version of the plan.
 * In particular, populate [7h0].
2. I will show the current version of the plan to one person and get their feedback.
 * In that process, I will try to address the issues I've outlined above.
3. I will add as much of their feedback to the plan as possible, keeping their identity anonymous if requested, though I have a strong preference for people's opinions to be public.
4. Iterate on this process and the plan.

### Non-interference stance

It's hard to understand a person's point of view when your own gets in the way. This is why I'm going to follow these guidelines when having one-on-ones with people:

1. My goal is not to make anyone do anything they don't want to do.
2. My goal is not to get the person to adopt the plan.
3. My goal is to explain various parts of the plan to a person, then understand and integrate their feedback into the plan.
4. My goal is for the person to be happy with the way their feedback was integrated into the plan.

In fact, if this approach works well, I'd be happy to take this to its logical conclusion of having a class of participant who are forbidden from interfering in AI development landscape.

### The plan keeper

A lot of the plan will come from one-on-one discussions. If all the conversations are stored in one person's mind, they can have future conversations much better. However, if the past conversations were done by two people, than each person can only bring half of all the relevant information.

### Measure of success

First measure of success is how many people sign off on how much of the plan.

Second measure of success is if people follow the plan and it's helpful.
